ht|f|at|It sometimes happens that a defender has a long and strong trump over or behind your trump holding and you need an  extra trump trick to make your contract or worse, you cannot lose even one trick to the outstanding trumps. 

You may learn about such hostile holdings from the bidding  -  for example, you were doubled @- or you discover  that in the early play. 

Every so often you may discover that a defender has finesseable trumps but you cannot finesse, because:
^c@2
1.  Dummy's trumps are gone because you drew them.
2.  You don't have a sufficient number of entries to dummy for the required number of finesses.
3.  You used, or need to use, dummy's trumps for other important purposes.
^b@2
If you are aware of the situation in time, you can often rescue yourself if you stop leading trumps and go after ruffs, trying  to perform a trump endplay.
|lg|8|at|
For a trump endplay to work, you should apply the "Trump reducing" technique. 

You do that by ruffing yourself down until you have equal or fewer trumps than those held by the opponent.

Meanwhile, you cash winners in side suits.

Finally you throw in the proper defender so he must concede the required trump trick.

Look at the following deal:|

